{"title_page": "Gondi people", "text_new": "\n\n== The Gonds ==\n {{short description|Ethnic group of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Gonds\n| native_name = Koitur\n| image = File:Women in adivasi village, Umaria district, India.jpg\n| caption = Gondi women in [[Umaria district]]\n| population = '''{{Circa|13 million|lk=yes}}'''\n| total_ref = <ref name=Census2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/ST.html|title=A-11 Individual Scheduled Tribe Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix|accessdate=24 March 2017|work=Census of India 2011|publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India|Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India]]}}</ref>\n| popplace = India\n| region1 = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| pop1 = 5,093,124\n| ref1 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region2 = [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| pop2 = 4,298,404\n| ref2 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region3 = [[Maharashtra]]\n| pop3 = 1,618,090\n| ref3 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region4 = [[Odisha]]\n| pop4 = 888,581\n| ref4 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region5 = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| pop5 = 569,035\n| ref5 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region6 = [[Andhra Pradesh]] (undivided)\n| pop6 = 304,537\n| ref6 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region7 = [[Bihar]]\n| pop7 = 256,738\n| ref7 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region8 = [[Karnataka]]\n| pop8 = 158,243\n| ref8 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region9 = [[Jharkhand]]\n| pop9 = 53,676\n| ref9 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region10 = [[West Bengal]]\n| pop10 = 13,535\n| ref10 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region11 = [[Gujarat]]\n| pop11 = 2,965\n| ref11 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| languages = [[Gondi language|Gondi]] \u2022 [[Hindi]] \u2022 [[Marathi language|Marathi]] \u2022 [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| religions = [[Hinduism]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/SCST-Series/ST14.html|title=ST-14 Scheduled Tribe Population By Religious Community|publisher=Census of India Website : Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| related = [[Dravidian people]] \u2022 [[Muria people]] \u2022 [[Madia Gond]]\n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\nThe '''Gond''' (G\u014dnd) or ''Koitur'''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Poyam |first1=Akash |title=The Gond\n=== \n== Heading text ==\n ===\n community is reclaiming their linguistic identity despite the state's historical biases |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/culture/gond-gondi-koitur-dictionary-adivasi |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=The Caravan |date=9 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> are an Indian ethnic group. They speak [[Gondi language]] which is a [[Dravidian language]]. They are one of the largest tribal groups in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.everyculture.com/wc/Germany-to-Jamaica/Gonds.html|title=Gonds|website=everyculture}}</ref> They are spread over the states of [[Madhya Pradesh]], eastern [[Maharashtra]] ([[Vidarbha]]),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X39c2VODLT0C&pg=PA16|title=The Gonds of Vidarbha|first=Shashishekhar Gopal|last=Deogaonkar|date=23 November 2017|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=9788180694745}}</ref> [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Telangana]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bihar]] and [[Western Odisha|Odisha]]. They are listed as a [[Scheduled Tribe]] for the purpose of India's [[Reservation in India|system of positive discrimination]].<ref name=list>{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107225208/http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |archivedate=7 November 2013 }}</ref> They are an [[Adivasi]] group (indigenous people) of India<ref>{{cite book|title=Adivasi Rights and Exclusion in India|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EiBtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT99&dq=gond+adivasi#v=onepage&q=gond%20adivasi&f=false|date=2018|isbn = 9780429792861|last1 = Srinivasa Rao|first1 = V.}}</ref>\n\nThe Gond are also known as the ''Raj Gond''. The term was widely used in 1950s, but has now become almost obsolete, probably because of the political eclipse of the Gond Rajas.<ref name=\"verma\">{{cite book |title=Indian Tribes Through the Ages |first=R. C. |last=Verma |publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India |year=2002 |isbn=978-8-12300-328-3}}</ref>{{page needed|date=February 2017}} The [[Gondi language]] is closely related to the [[Telugu language|Telugu]], belonging to the [[Dravidian language family|Dravidian]] family of languages. The [[2011 Census of India]] recorded about 2.98 million Gondi speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011Census/C-16_25062018_NEW.pdf|title=Census of India 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 1971 census, their population was 5.01 million. By the 1991 census, this had increased to 9.3 million<ref name=\"verma\"/>{{page needed|date=February 2017}} and by the 2001 census the figure was nearly 11 million. For the past few decades they have been witnesses to the [[Naxalite\u2013Maoist insurgency]] in the central part of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/bringing-rural-realities-on-stage-in-urban-india/article7592193.ece|title=Bringing rural realities on stage in urban India|first=Omar|last=Rashid|date=29 August 2015|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Gondi people, at the behest of the Chhattisgarh government, formed the [[Salwa Judum]], an armed militant group to fight the Naxalite insurgency.<ref>{{cite news |title=Salwa Judum is the only effective weapon against Maoist terror at present |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/salwa-judum-is-the-only-effective-weapon-against-maoist-terror-at-present-strengthen-it/story-liLxecdkR5hKTAVDtv6eBK.html |work=Hindustan Times |date=6 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nScholars believe that Gonds ruled in [[Gondwana (India)|Gondwana]], now in eastern Madhya Pradesh and western Odisha, between the 13th and 19th centuries AD. Muslim writers described a rise of Gond state after the 14th century.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nGonds ruled in four kingdoms ([[Garha Kingdom|Garha-Mandla]], Deogarh, Chanda, and Kherla) in central India between the 16th and 18th centuries. [[Rani Durgavati]] rules the region from 1550 until her death in 1564. They built number of forts, palaces, temples, tanks and lakes during the rule of the Gonds dynasty. The Gondwana kingdom survived until the late 16th century. They also gained control over the Malwa after the decline of the Mughals followed by the Marathas in 1690.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} The [[Maratha Empire|Maratha]] power swept into Gondland in the 1740s. The Marathas overthrew the Gond Rajas (princes) and seized most of their territory, while Some Gond zamindaris (estates) survived until recently.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Concept of Race in South Asia |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Delhi |year=1995 |editor-first=Peter |editor-last=Robb |first=Crispin |last=Bates |chapter=Race, Caste and Tribe in Central India: the early origins of Indian ...anthropomorphize |isbn=978-0-19-563767-0 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PwNkQgAACAAJ |page=233 |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Ancient astronomy==\nMany astronomical ideas were known to ancient Gonds.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vahia |first1=M.N. |last2=Halkare |first2=Ganesh |title=Spects of Gond astronomy |journal=Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage |date=2013 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=29\u201344 |arxiv=1306.2416 |bibcode=2013JAHH...16...29V }}</ref> Gonds had their own local terms for the Sun, Moon, Milky Way, and constellations. Most of these ideas were basis for their time-keeping and calendrical activities.{{efn|The [[Banjara]]s and [[Kolam people|Kolams]] are also known to have knowledge of astronomy.<ref name='\"arxiv.org\"'>{{cite journal |last1=Vahia |first1=M.N. |last2=Halkare |first2=Ganesh |last3=Menon |first3=Kishore |last4=Calamur |first4=Harini |title=The astronomy of two Indian tribes: the Banjaras and the Kolams |journal=Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage |date=2014 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=65\u201384 |arxiv=1406.3044 |bibcode=2014JAHH...17...65V }}</ref>}}\n\n==Religion==\nMost Gonds follow folk [[Hinduism]], which retains the [[animism|animist]] beliefs of nature, and ancestor worship.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Murkute |first1=S. R. |title=Socio-Cultural Study of Scheduled Tribes |page=155 |via=Google Books |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X2gpF5bsAjUC&pg=PA155 |year=1984 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |series=Everyday Cultures |title=Gonds |url=https://www.everyculture.com/wc/Germany-to-Jamaica/Gonds.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Mehta |first1=B.H. |title=Gonds of the Central Indian Highlands |page=118 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wpfUwRl24lgC&pg=PA118 |accessdate=26 February 2019 |isbn=9788170222620 |year=1990}}</ref> Some Gonds also practice [[Sarnaism]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Human: The definitive visual guide |publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2004 |isbn=0-7566-0520-2 |editor-last=Winston |editor-first=Robert |location=New York, NY |page=438}}</ref> Pola, a cattle festival, [[Naga panchami]], and [[Dassera]] are their major festivals.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nGonds worship a high god known as '''''Baradeo''''', whose alternate names are ''[[Bhagavan]]'', ''Sri Shambu Mahadeo'', and ''Persa Pen''. Baradeo oversees activities of lesser gods such as clan and village deities, as well as ancestors.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Baradeo is respected but he does not receive fervent devotion, which is shown only to clan and village deities, ancestors, and totems.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Gond |title=Gond (people) |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica |access-date=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany Gonds worship [[Ravana]], whom they consider to be the tenth ''dharmaguru'' of their people and the ancestor-king of one of their four lineages. They also worship Kupar Lingo as their supreme deity and their ancestor before Ravana. On [[Dussehra]], the Gondi inhabitants of [[Paraswadi]] carry an image of Ravana riding an elephant in a procession to worship him, and protest the burning of Ravana's effigies.{{efn|The Gonds\u2019 worship of Ravana is also a vehicle for resisting pressure from Christian missionaries and right-wing Hindu groups, and to preserve the distinct Gond culture.}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/asuras-no-just-indians/291677 |title=Asuras? No, just Indians |magazine=Outlook India |id=291677}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/omar-rashid-on-ravan-worship/article7799972.ece |title=Celebrating Ravan |newspaper=The Hindu |id=article&nbsp;7799972}}</ref>\n\nTheir typical reaction to death has been described as one of anger, because Gonds believe death is caused magically, by demons.<ref>{{cite book |last=Santrock |first=John W. |title=Life-Span Development |year=2017 |publisher=McGraw Hill |isbn=9781259254833 |page=598 |edition=16th International}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\nThey are a designated [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribe]] in Andhra Pradesh, parts of Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Chhattisgarh, Gujarat, Jharkhand, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, Telangana, Odisha and West Bengal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]] had classified the Gondi people as a [[Scheduled Caste]] but by 2007, they were one of several groups that the Uttar Pradesh government had redesignated as [[Scheduled Tribes]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=State At A Glance - Uttar Pradesh |date=July 2007 |journal=Pratiyogita Darpan |volume=2 |issue=13 |page=81|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7egDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT72|last1=Darpan |first1=Pratiyogita }}</ref> As of 2017, that tribal designation applies only to certain districts, not the entire state.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tribal.nic.in/WriteReadData/CMS/Documents/201212010356439267578File1068.pdf |title=State wise Scheduled Tribes&nbsp;\u2014 Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Ministry of Tribal Affairs, Government of India |accessdate=4 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123041643/http://tribal.nic.in/WriteReadData/CMS/Documents/201212010356439267578File1068.pdf |archivedate=23 November 2016 }}</ref> The [[2011 Census of India]] for Uttar Pradesh showed the Scheduled Caste Gond population as 21,992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/SC_ST/PCA-A10/SC-0900-PCA-A-10-ddw.xlsx |title= A-10 Individual Scheduled Caste Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix - Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Godha]]\n* [[Ajanbahu Jatbasha]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|1}}{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* The tribal art of middle India - [[Verrier Elwin]] - 1951\n* Savaging the Civilized, Verrier Elwin, His Tribals & India - Ramachandra Guha - The University of Chicago Press - 1999\n* Beine, David m. 1994. A sociolinguistic survey of the Gondi-speaking communities of central India. M.A. thesis. San Diego State University. 516 p.\n* Banerjee, B. G., and Kiran Bhatia. ''Tribal Demography of Gonds''. Delhi: Gian Pub. House, 1988. {{ISBN|81-212-0237-X}}\n* Elwin, Verrier. ''Phulmat of the Hills; A Tale of the Gonds''. London: J. Murray, 1937.\n* F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf, Christoph von, and Elizabeth von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf. ''The Gonds of Andhra Pradesh: Tradition and Change in an Indian Tribe''. London: George Allen & Unwin, 1979. {{ISBN|0-04-301090-3}}\n* Kaufmann, Walter. ''Songs and Drummings of the Hill Maria, Jhoria Muria and Bastar Muria Gonds. And, the Musical Instruments of the Marias and Murias''. 1950.\n* Mehta, B. H. ''Gonds of the Central Indian Highlands: A Study of the Dynamics of Gond Society''. New Delhi: Concept, 1984.\n* Museum of Mankind, Shelagh Weir, and Hira Lal. ''The Gonds of Central India; The Material Culture of the Gonds of Chhindwara District, Madhya Pradesh''. London: British Museum, 1973. {{ISBN|0-7141-1537-1}}\n* Pagdi, Setumadhava Rao. ''Among the Gonds of Adilabad''. Bombay: Popular Book Depot, 1952.\n* Pingle, Urmila, and Christoph von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf. ''Gonds and Their Neighbours: A Study in Genetic Diversity''. Lucknow, India: Ethnographic & Folk Culture Society, 1987.\n* Sharma, Anima. ''Tribe in Transition: A Study of Thakur Gonds''. India: Mittal Publications, 2005. {{ISBN|81-7099-989-8}}\n* Singh, Indrajit. ''The Gondwana and the Gonds''. Lucknow, India: The Universal publishers, 1944.\n* Kangalee, Motiram Chhabiram, Paree Kupar Lingo Gondi Punemi Darshan (In Hindi)'',''Publisher ujjvala society Nagpur,2011\n* Vatti, Jalpati,''Mava sagaa padeeng, in'' ''Gondwana sagaa Patrika'' published (In Hindi) in October 1986\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gondi people}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.folkpaintingsindia.com/ | title = Gond Tribal Art \u2014 Madhya Pradesh | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150622220138/http://www.folkpaintingsindia.com/ | archivedate = 22 June 2015 }}.\n* {{citation | url = http://www.artribal.com/ | title = Gond Tribal Art \u2014 Madhya Pradesh}}.\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5386418/ Reconstructing the population history of the largest tribe of India: the Dravidian speaking Gond]\n* {{citation | url = http://www.sinlung.com/ | title = Sinlung \u2014 Indian tribes}}.\n* {{citation | url = http://www.gondindia.org/ | title = Gond - The History }}.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXFqaqHJ8Xk \u00ab Animating Tribal Art \u00bb by Leslie MacKenzie and Tara Douglas with the Pardhan Gond artists], 8:16 \n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7AK0Lp51j0c Gond painting 2], 6:54\n\n''This article includes material from the 1995 [[public domain]] [[Library of Congress Country Studies|Library of Congress Country Study]] on India.''\n\n{{Scheduled tribes of India}}\n{{Western Odisha}}\n{{Nagpur}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gondi People}}\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Telangana]]\n[[Category:Dravidian peoples]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Odisha]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Jharkhand]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Schools of Indian painting]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Castes of Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ethnic group of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Gonds\n| native_name = Koitur\n| image = File:Women in adivasi village, Umaria district, India.jpg\n| caption = Gondi women in [[Umaria district]]\n| population = '''{{Circa|13 million|lk=yes}}'''\n| total_ref = <ref name=Census2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/ST.html|title=A-11 Individual Scheduled Tribe Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix|accessdate=24 March 2017|work=Census of India 2011|publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India|Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India]]}}</ref>\n| popplace = India\n| region1 = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| pop1 = 5,093,124\n| ref1 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region2 = [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| pop2 = 4,298,404\n| ref2 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region3 = [[Maharashtra]]\n| pop3 = 1,618,090\n| ref3 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region4 = [[Odisha]]\n| pop4 = 888,581\n| ref4 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region5 = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| pop5 = 569,035\n| ref5 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region6 = [[Andhra Pradesh]] (undivided)\n| pop6 = 304,537\n| ref6 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region7 = [[Bihar]]\n| pop7 = 256,738\n| ref7 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region8 = [[Karnataka]]\n| pop8 = 158,243\n| ref8 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region9 = [[Jharkhand]]\n| pop9 = 53,676\n| ref9 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region10 = [[West Bengal]]\n| pop10 = 13,535\n| ref10 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| region11 = [[Gujarat]]\n| pop11 = 2,965\n| ref11 = <ref name=Census2011/>\n| languages = [[Gondi language|Gondi]] \u2022 [[Hindi]] \u2022 [[Marathi language|Marathi]] \u2022 [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| religions = [[Hinduism]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/SCST-Series/ST14.html|title=ST-14 Scheduled Tribe Population By Religious Community|publisher=Census of India Website : Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| related = [[Dravidian people]] \u2022 [[Muria people]] \u2022 [[Madia Gond]]\n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\nThe '''Gondi''' (G\u014dndi) or '''Gond''' or '''Koitur'''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Poyam |first1=Akash |title=The Koitur community is reclaiming their linguistic identity despite the state's historical biases |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/culture/gond-gondi-koitur-dictionary-adivasi |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=The Caravan |date=9 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> are an Indian ethnic group. They speak [[Gondi language]] which is a [[Dravidian language]]. They are one of the largest tribal groups in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.everyculture.com/wc/Germany-to-Jamaica/Gonds.html|title=Gonds|website=everyculture}}</ref> They are spread over the states of [[Madhya Pradesh]], eastern [[Maharashtra]] ([[Vidarbha]]),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X39c2VODLT0C&pg=PA16|title=The Gonds of Vidarbha|first=Shashishekhar Gopal|last=Deogaonkar|date=23 November 2017|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=9788180694745}}</ref> [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Telangana]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bihar]] and [[Western Odisha|Odisha]]. They are listed as a [[Scheduled Tribe]] for the purpose of India's [[Reservation in India|system of positive discrimination]].<ref name=list>{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107225208/http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |archivedate=7 November 2013 }}</ref> They are an [[Adivasi]] group (indigenous people) of India<ref>{{cite book|title=Adivasi Rights and Exclusion in India|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EiBtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT99&dq=gond+adivasi#v=onepage&q=gond%20adivasi&f=false|date=2018|isbn = 9780429792861|last1 = Srinivasa Rao|first1 = V.}}</ref>\n\nThe Gond are also known as the ''Raj Gond''. The term was widely used in 1950s, but has now become almost obsolete, probably because of the political eclipse of the Gond Rajas.<ref name=\"verma\">{{cite book |title=Indian Tribes Through the Ages |first=R. C. |last=Verma |publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India |year=2002 |isbn=978-8-12300-328-3}}</ref>{{page needed|date=February 2017}} The [[Gondi language]] is closely related to the [[Telugu language|Telugu]], belonging to the [[Dravidian language family|Dravidian]] family of languages. The [[2011 Census of India]] recorded about 2.98 million Gondi speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011Census/C-16_25062018_NEW.pdf|title=Census of India 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 1971 census, their population was 5.01 million. By the 1991 census, this had increased to 9.3 million<ref name=\"verma\"/>{{page needed|date=February 2017}} and by the 2001 census the figure was nearly 11 million. For the past few decades they have been witnesses to the [[Naxalite\u2013Maoist insurgency]] in the central part of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/bringing-rural-realities-on-stage-in-urban-india/article7592193.ece|title=Bringing rural realities on stage in urban India|first=Omar|last=Rashid|date=29 August 2015|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Gondi people, at the behest of the Chhattisgarh government, formed the [[Salwa Judum]], an armed militant group to fight the Naxalite insurgency.<ref>{{cite news |title=Salwa Judum is the only effective weapon against Maoist terror at present |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/salwa-judum-is-the-only-effective-weapon-against-maoist-terror-at-present-strengthen-it/story-liLxecdkR5hKTAVDtv6eBK.html |work=Hindustan Times |date=6 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nScholars believe that Gonds ruled in [[Gondwana (India)|Gondwana]], now in eastern Madhya Pradesh and western Odisha, between the 13th and 19th centuries AD. Muslim writers described a rise of Gond state after the 14th century.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nGonds ruled in four kingdoms ([[Garha Kingdom|Garha-Mandla]], Deogarh, Chanda, and Kherla) in central India between the 16th and 18th centuries. [[Rani Durgavati]] rules the region from 1550 until her death in 1564. They built number of forts, palaces, temples, tanks and lakes during the rule of the Gonds dynasty. The Gondwana kingdom survived until the late 16th century. They also gained control over the Malwa after the decline of the Mughals followed by the Marathas in 1690.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} The [[Maratha Empire|Maratha]] power swept into Gondland in the 1740s. The Marathas overthrew the Gond Rajas (princes) and seized most of their territory, while Some Gond zamindaris (estates) survived until recently.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Concept of Race in South Asia |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Delhi |year=1995 |editor-first=Peter |editor-last=Robb |first=Crispin |last=Bates |chapter=Race, Caste and Tribe in Central India: the early origins of Indian ...anthropomorphize |isbn=978-0-19-563767-0 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PwNkQgAACAAJ |page=233 |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Ancient astronomy==\nMany astronomical ideas were known to ancient Gonds.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vahia |first1=M.N. |last2=Halkare |first2=Ganesh |title=Spects of Gond astronomy |journal=Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage |date=2013 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=29\u201344 |arxiv=1306.2416 |bibcode=2013JAHH...16...29V }}</ref> Gonds had their own local terms for the Sun, Moon, Milky Way, and constellations. Most of these ideas were basis for their time-keeping and calendrical activities.{{efn|The [[Banjara]]s and [[Kolam people|Kolams]] are also known to have knowledge of astronomy.<ref name='\"arxiv.org\"'>{{cite journal |last1=Vahia |first1=M.N. |last2=Halkare |first2=Ganesh |last3=Menon |first3=Kishore |last4=Calamur |first4=Harini |title=The astronomy of two Indian tribes: the Banjaras and the Kolams |journal=Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage |date=2014 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=65\u201384 |arxiv=1406.3044 |bibcode=2014JAHH...17...65V }}</ref>}}\n\n==Religion==\nMost Gonds follow folk [[Hinduism]], which retains the [[animism|animist]] beliefs of nature, and ancestor worship.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Murkute |first1=S. R. |title=Socio-Cultural Study of Scheduled Tribes |page=155 |via=Google Books |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X2gpF5bsAjUC&pg=PA155 |year=1984 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |series=Everyday Cultures |title=Gonds |url=https://www.everyculture.com/wc/Germany-to-Jamaica/Gonds.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Mehta |first1=B.H. |title=Gonds of the Central Indian Highlands |page=118 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wpfUwRl24lgC&pg=PA118 |accessdate=26 February 2019 |isbn=9788170222620 |year=1990}}</ref> Some Gonds also practice [[Sarnaism]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Human: The definitive visual guide |publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2004 |isbn=0-7566-0520-2 |editor-last=Winston |editor-first=Robert |location=New York, NY |page=438}}</ref> Pola, a cattle festival, [[Naga panchami]], and [[Dassera]] are their major festivals.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nGonds worship a high god known as '''''Baradeo''''', whose alternate names are ''[[Bhagavan]]'', ''Sri Shambu Mahadeo'', and ''Persa Pen''. Baradeo oversees activities of lesser gods such as clan and village deities, as well as ancestors.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Baradeo is respected but he does not receive fervent devotion, which is shown only to clan and village deities, ancestors, and totems.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Gond |title=Gond (people) |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica |access-date=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany Gonds worship [[Ravana]], whom they consider to be the tenth ''dharmaguru'' of their people and the ancestor-king of one of their four lineages. They also worship Kupar Lingo as their supreme deity and their ancestor before Ravana. On [[Dussehra]], the Gondi inhabitants of [[Paraswadi]] carry an image of Ravana riding an elephant in a procession to worship him, and protest the burning of Ravana's effigies.{{efn|The Gonds\u2019 worship of Ravana is also a vehicle for resisting pressure from Christian missionaries and right-wing Hindu groups, and to preserve the distinct Gond culture.}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/asuras-no-just-indians/291677 |title=Asuras? No, just Indians |magazine=Outlook India |id=291677}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/omar-rashid-on-ravan-worship/article7799972.ece |title=Celebrating Ravan |newspaper=The Hindu |id=article&nbsp;7799972}}</ref>\n\nTheir typical reaction to death has been described as one of anger, because Gonds believe death is caused magically, by demons.<ref>{{cite book |last=Santrock |first=John W. |title=Life-Span Development |year=2017 |publisher=McGraw Hill |isbn=9781259254833 |page=598 |edition=16th International}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\nThey are a designated [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribe]] in Andhra Pradesh, parts of Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Chhattisgarh, Gujarat, Jharkhand, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, Telangana, Odisha and West Bengal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]] had classified the Gondi people as a [[Scheduled Caste]] but by 2007, they were one of several groups that the Uttar Pradesh government had redesignated as [[Scheduled Tribes]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=State At A Glance - Uttar Pradesh |date=July 2007 |journal=Pratiyogita Darpan |volume=2 |issue=13 |page=81|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7egDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT72|last1=Darpan |first1=Pratiyogita }}</ref> As of 2017, that tribal designation applies only to certain districts, not the entire state.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tribal.nic.in/WriteReadData/CMS/Documents/201212010356439267578File1068.pdf |title=State wise Scheduled Tribes&nbsp;\u2014 Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Ministry of Tribal Affairs, Government of India |accessdate=4 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123041643/http://tribal.nic.in/WriteReadData/CMS/Documents/201212010356439267578File1068.pdf |archivedate=23 November 2016 }}</ref> The [[2011 Census of India]] for Uttar Pradesh showed the Scheduled Caste Gond population as 21,992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/SC_ST/PCA-A10/SC-0900-PCA-A-10-ddw.xlsx |title= A-10 Individual Scheduled Caste Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix - Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India |accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Godha]]\n* [[Ajanbahu Jatbasha]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|1}}{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* The tribal art of middle India - [[Verrier Elwin]] - 1951\n* Savaging the Civilized, Verrier Elwin, His Tribals & India - Ramachandra Guha - The University of Chicago Press - 1999\n* Beine, David m. 1994. A sociolinguistic survey of the Gondi-speaking communities of central India. M.A. thesis. San Diego State University. 516 p.\n* Banerjee, B. G., and Kiran Bhatia. ''Tribal Demography of Gonds''. Delhi: Gian Pub. House, 1988. {{ISBN|81-212-0237-X}}\n* Elwin, Verrier. ''Phulmat of the Hills; A Tale of the Gonds''. London: J. Murray, 1937.\n* F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf, Christoph von, and Elizabeth von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf. ''The Gonds of Andhra Pradesh: Tradition and Change in an Indian Tribe''. London: George Allen & Unwin, 1979. {{ISBN|0-04-301090-3}}\n* Kaufmann, Walter. ''Songs and Drummings of the Hill Maria, Jhoria Muria and Bastar Muria Gonds. And, the Musical Instruments of the Marias and Murias''. 1950.\n* Mehta, B. H. ''Gonds of the Central Indian Highlands: A Study of the Dynamics of Gond Society''. New Delhi: Concept, 1984.\n* Museum of Mankind, Shelagh Weir, and Hira Lal. ''The Gonds of Central India; The Material Culture of the Gonds of Chhindwara District, Madhya Pradesh''. London: British Museum, 1973. {{ISBN|0-7141-1537-1}}\n* Pagdi, Setumadhava Rao. ''Among the Gonds of Adilabad''. Bombay: Popular Book Depot, 1952.\n* Pingle, Urmila, and Christoph von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf. ''Gonds and Their Neighbours: A Study in Genetic Diversity''. Lucknow, India: Ethnographic & Folk Culture Society, 1987.\n* Sharma, Anima. ''Tribe in Transition: A Study of Thakur Gonds''. India: Mittal Publications, 2005. {{ISBN|81-7099-989-8}}\n* Singh, Indrajit. ''The Gondwana and the Gonds''. Lucknow, India: The Universal publishers, 1944.\n* Kangalee, Motiram Chhabiram, Paree Kupar Lingo Gondi Punemi Darshan (In Hindi)'',''Publisher ujjvala society Nagpur,2011\n* Vatti, Jalpati,''Mava sagaa padeeng, in'' ''Gondwana sagaa Patrika'' published (In Hindi) in October 1986\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gondi people}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.folkpaintingsindia.com/ | title = Gond Tribal Art \u2014 Madhya Pradesh | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150622220138/http://www.folkpaintingsindia.com/ | archivedate = 22 June 2015 }}.\n* {{citation | url = http://www.artribal.com/ | title = Gond Tribal Art \u2014 Madhya Pradesh}}.\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5386418/ Reconstructing the population history of the largest tribe of India: the Dravidian speaking Gond]\n* {{citation | url = http://www.sinlung.com/ | title = Sinlung \u2014 Indian tribes}}.\n* {{citation | url = http://www.gondindia.org/ | title = Gond - The History }}.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXFqaqHJ8Xk \u00ab Animating Tribal Art \u00bb by Leslie MacKenzie and Tara Douglas with the Pardhan Gond artists], 8:16 \n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7AK0Lp51j0c Gond painting 2], 6:54\n\n''This article includes material from the 1995 [[public domain]] [[Library of Congress Country Studies|Library of Congress Country Study]] on India.''\n\n{{Scheduled tribes of India}}\n{{Western Odisha}}\n{{Nagpur}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gondi People}}\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Telangana]]\n[[Category:Dravidian peoples]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Uttar Pradesh]