=6898 |pages=689\u2013695 |year=2002 |last1=Pauly |first1=Daniel |last2=Christensen |first2=Villy |last3=Gu\u00e9nette |first3=Sylvie |last4=Pitcher |first4=Tony J. |last5=Sumaila |first5=U. Rashid |last6=Walters |first6=Carl J. |last7=Watson |first7=R. |last8=Zeller |first8=Dirk }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1038/439029a |pmid=16397489 |title=Deep-sea fishes qualify as endangered |journal=Nature |volume=439 |issue=7072 |pages=29 |year=2006 |last1=Devine |first1=Jennifer A. |last2=Baker |first2=Krista D. |last3=Haedrich |first3=Richard L. }}\n* [http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/baselines/index.htm Shifting Environmental Baselines]\n* [http://news.mongabay.com/2008/0908-hance_interview_jacquet.html \"An Interview with Jennifer Jacquet: Small-scale fisheries are \"best hope\" for sustainability in developing world] ''[[Mongabay.com]]'', September 8, 2008.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714112247/http://conservation.mongabay.com/news/Overfishing.html Overfishing] ''[[Mongabay.com]]''.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927181547/http://www.seaweb.org/resources/citations/fisheries/2006/06fishmanindex.php Fisheries Management: 2006 Publications]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927181544/http://www.seaweb.org/resources/citations/fisheries/2007/07fishmanindex.php Fisheries Management: 2007 Publications]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927181602/http://www.seaweb.org/resources/citations/fisheries/2008/FisheriesFisheriesManagement2008.php Fisheries Management: 2008 Publications]\n* [http://www.marinebio.com/Oceans/Conservation/sustainable-fisheries.asp Sustainable Fisheries] ''MarineBio''.\n* [http://www.fisheries.ubc.ca/publications/reports/FCReport2006-2007web.pdf 2006-2007 Report] ''[[UBC Fisheries Centre]]''.\n\n; recent references and imbroglio\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1890/ES10-00142.1 |title=Do rebuttals affect future science? |journal=Ecosphere |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=art37 |year=2011 |last1=Banobi |first1=Jeannette A. |last2=Branch |first2=Trevor A. |last3=Hilborn |first3=Ray }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature09528 |pmid=21085178 |title=The trophic fingerprint of marine fisheries |journal=Nature |volume=468 |issue=7322 |pages=431\u2013435 |year=2010 |last1=Branch |first1=Trevor A. |last2=Watson |first2=Reg |last3=Fulton |first3=Elizabeth A. |last4=Jennings |first4=Simon |last5=McGilliard |first5=Carey R. |last6=Pablico |first6=Grace T. |last7=Ricard |first7=Daniel |last8=Tracey |first8=Sean R. }}\n* Hilborn R (2010) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120601225512/http://www.atsea.org/doc/Hilborn%202010%20Science%20Chronicles%202010-11-1.pdf \"Apocalypse forestalled: why all the world\u2019s fisheries aren\u2019t collapsing\"] Nature Conservancy, ''Science Chronicles'',  November 2010, pp.&nbsp;5\u20139.\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.3989/scimar.2009.73n2215 |title=Beyond duplicity and ignorance in global fisheries |journal=Scientia Marina |volume=73 |issue=2 |pages=215\u2013224 |year=2009 |last1=Pauly |first1=Daniel }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.marpol.2011.10.021 |title=Comments on FAO's State of Fisheries and Aquaculture, or 'SOFIA 2010' |journal=Marine Policy |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=746\u2013752 |year=2012 |last1=Pauly |first1=Daniel |last2=Froese |first2=Rainer }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.1003236107 |pmid=20566867 |pmc=2901455 |title=Global fishery development patterns are driven by profit but not trophic level |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=107 |issue=27 |pages=12163\u201312167 |year=2010 |last1=Sethi |first1=S. A. |last2=Branch |first2=T. A. |last3=Watson |first3=R. }}\n* Taylor WA, AJ Lynch and M Schechter (Eds) (2011) ''Sustainable Fisheries: Multi-level Approaches to a Global Problem'', American Fisheries Society. {{ISBN|978-1-934874-21-9}}. [http://afsbooks.org/afs/review/55064P.pdf Review]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* Watson R, Zeller D and Pauly D (2011) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130513035531/http://www.wwf.be/_media/Sea-Around-Us-EU_fleet-expansion_Jan-18-2012_lowres1_303615.pdf \"Spatial expansion of EU and non-EU fishing fleets into the global ocean, 1950 to the present\"] ''Sea Around Us'', Report commissioned by WWF Netherlands.\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1173146 |pmid=19644114 |title=Rebuilding Global Fisheries |journal=Science |volume=325 |issue=5940 |pages=578\u2013585 |year=2009 |last1=Worm |first1=B. |last2=Hilborn |first2=R. |last3=Baum |first3=J. K. |last4=Branch |first4=T. A. |last5=Collie |first5=J. S. |last6=Costello |first6=C. |last7=Fogarty |first7=M. J. |last8=Fulton |first8=E. A. |last9=Hutchings |first9=J. A. |last10=Jennings |first10=S. |last11=Jensen |first11=O. P. |last12=Lotze |first12=H. K. |last13=Mace |first13=P. M. |last14=McClanahan |first14=T. R. |last15=Minto |first15=C. |last16=Palumbi |first16=S. R. |last17=Parma |first17=A. M. |last18=Ricard |first18=D. |last19=Rosenberg |first19=A. A. |last20=Watson |first20=R. |last21=Zeller |first21=D. |citeseerx=10.1.1.417.4642 }}\n\n{{Fishery science topics|expanded=management}}\n\n\n[[Category:Sustainable fishery| ]]\n[[Category:Fish conservation]]\n\n[[ja:\u30d5\u30a3\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30b5\u30b9\u30c6\u30ca\u30d3\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Seawifs global biosphere Centered on the Pacific.jpg|thumb|400px|right|[[SeaWiFS]] map showing the levels of [[primary production]] in the world's oceans]]\n[[File:Primary production to sustain global marine fisheries.png|thumb|400px|right|Primary production required (PPR) to sustain global marine fisheries landings expressed as percentage of local primary production (PP).Estimates of PPR, PP and PPR/PP computed per 0.5\u00b0 latitude/longitude ocean cells. PPR estimates based on the [www.seaaroundus.org Sea Around Us] catch database and PP estimates derived from SeaWiFS's global ocean colour satellite data. The maps represent total annual landings for 1950 (top) and 2005 (bottom). Note that PP estimates are static and derived from the synoptic observation for 1998.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0015143 |pmid=21151994 |pmc=2996307 |title=The Spatial Expansion and Ecological Footprint of Fisheries (1950 to Present) |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=5 |issue=12 |pages=e15143 |year=2010 |last1=Swartz |first1=Wilf |last2=Sala |first2=Enric |last3=Tracey |first3=Sean |last4=Watson |first4=Reg |last5=Pauly |first5=Daniel }}</ref>]]\n\nA conventional idea of a '''sustainable fishery''' is that it is one that is harvested at a sustainable rate, where the fish population does not decline over time because of fishing practices. [[Sustainability]] in [[fisheries]] combines theoretical disciplines, such as the [[population dynamics of fisheries]], with practical strategies, such as avoiding [[overfishing]] through techniques such as [[IFQ|individual fishing quotas]], curtailing [[destructive fishing practices|destructive]] and [[Illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing|illegal fishing practices]] by lobbying for appropriate law and policy, setting up protected areas, restoring collapsed fisheries, incorporating all externalities involved in harvesting marine ecosystems into fishery economics, educating stakeholders and the wider public, and developing independent certification programs.\n\nSome primary concerns around sustainability are that heavy fishing pressures, such as [[overexploitation]] and [[Growth overfishing|growth]] or [[recruitment overfishing]], will result in the loss of significant [[sustainable yield|potential yield]]; that [[Fish stock|stock]] structure will erode to the point where it loses diversity and resilience to environmental fluctuations; that ecosystems and their economic infrastructures will cycle between collapse and recovery; with each cycle less productive than its predecessor; and that changes will occur in the [[Trophic level|trophic]] balance  ([[fishing down marine food webs]]).<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\">\n[[Ray Hilborn|Hilborn, Ray]] (2005) [https://books.google.com/books?id=J-2JcCC_Yn0C&pg=PP1 \"Are Sustainable Fisheries Achievable?\"] Chapter 15, pp. 247\u2013259, in Norse and Crowder (2005).</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n{{quotebox|''Sustainable management of fisheries cannot be achieved without an acceptance that the long-term goals of fisheries management are the same as those of environmental conservation''|[[Daniel Pauly]] and Dave Preikshot|<ref name=\"Preikshot&Pauly2005\">\nPreikshot, Dave and [[Daniel Pauly|Pauly, Daniel]] (2005) [https://books.google.com/books?id=J-2JcCC_Yn0C&pg=PA185 \"Global Fisheries and Marine Conservation: Is Coexistence Possible?\"] Chapter 11, pp. 185\u2013197, in Norse and Crowder (2005).</ref> |width  = 30% |align  = right}}\n\nGlobal [[wild fisheries]] are believed to have peaked and begun a decline, with valuable habitats, such as [[estuaries]] and [[coral reef]]s, in critical condition.<ref>[[Tietenberg, Tom]] (2006) ''Environmental and Natural Resource Economics: A Contemporary Approach''. Page 28. Pearson/Addison Wesley. {{ISBN|978-0-321-30504-6}}</ref> Current [[aquaculture]] or [[fish farm|farming]] of [[piscivorous]] fish, such as [[salmon]], does not solve the problem because farmed piscivores are fed products from wild fish, such as [[forage fish]]. [[Aquaculture of salmon|Salmon farming]] also has major [[Aquaculture of salmon#Issues|negative impacts]] on wild salmon.<ref name=\"Salmon Run\">Knapp G, Roheim CA and Anderson JL (2007) [https://www.traffic.org/site/assets/files/3637/great-salmon-run.pdf = The+Great+Salmon+Run&col=&n=4 ''The Great Salmon Run: Competition Between Wild And Farmed Salmon''] [[World Wildlife Fund]]. {{ISBN|0-89164-175-0}}</ref><ref>Washington Post. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/13/AR2007121301190.html Salmon Farming May Doom Wild Populations, Study Says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912194450/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/13/AR2007121301190.html |date=2016-09-12 }}.</ref> Fish that occupy the higher [[trophic level]]s are less efficient sources of food energy.\n\nFishery ecosystems are an important subset of the wider marine environment. This article documents the views of [[fisheries science|fisheries scientists]] and [[marine conservation]]ists about innovative approaches towards sustainable fisheries.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==History==\n{{quotebox|''In the end, we will conserve only what we love; we will love only what we understand; and we will understand only what we are taught''|Senegalese conservationist [[Baba Dioum]]|<ref>\nNorse & Crowder 2005, [https://web.archive.org/web/20180430223634/https://books.google.com/books?id=J-2JcCC_Yn0C&pg=PR19&vq=%22In+the+end+we+will+conserve+only+what+we+love,+we+will+love+only+what+we+understand,+and+we+will%22&source=gbs_quotes_r&cad=6#v=onepage&q=%22In%20the%20end%20we%20will%20conserve%20only%20what%20we%20love%2C%20we%20will%20love%20only%20what%20we%20understand%2C%20and%20we%20will%22&f=false Page xix]</ref> |width  = 30% |align  = right}}\n\nIn his 1883 inaugural address to the International Fisheries Exhibition in London, [[Thomas Huxley]] asserted that overfishing or \"permanent exhaustion\" was scientifically impossible, and stated that probably \"all the great sea fisheries are inexhaustible\".<ref>\nHuxley, Thomas (1883)[http://aleph0.clarku.edu/huxley/SM5/fish.html Inaugural Address] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110829062507/http://aleph0.clarku.edu/huxley/SM5/fish.html |date=2011-08-29 }} Fisheries Exhibition, London.</ref> In reality, by 1883 marine fisheries were already collapsing. The [[United States Fish Commission]] was established 12 years earlier for the purpose of finding why fisheries in [[New England]] were declining. At the time of Huxley's address, the Atlantic [[halibut]] fishery had already collapsed (and has never recovered).<ref>\nGoode GB and Collins JW (1887) \"The fresh-halibut fishery\". In: ''The fisheries and fishery industry of the United States''. Section V. History and methods of the fisheries, Vol. I, Part I. Government Printing Office, Washington, DC. p. 3\u201389.</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Traditional management of fisheries===\nTraditionally, [[fisheries management]] and the science underpinning it was distorted by its \"narrow focus on [[Population dynamics of fisheries|target populations]] and the corresponding failure to account for ecosystem effects leading to declines of species abundance and diversity\" and by perceiving the fishing industry as \"the sole legitimate user, in effect the owner, of marine living resources.\" Historically, stock assessment scientists usually worked in government laboratories and considered their work to be providing services to the fishing industry. These scientists dismissed conservation issues and distanced themselves from the scientists and the science that raised the issues. This happened even as commercial fish stocks deteriorated, and even though many governments were signatories to binding conservation agreements.<ref name=\"Preikshot&Pauly2005\" />\n\n==Defining sustainability==\n\n[[Ray Hilborn]], of the [[University of Washington]], distinguishes three ways of defining a sustainable fishery:\n\n* ''Long term constant yield'' is the idea that undisturbed nature establishes a steady state that changes little over time. Properly done, fishing at up to [[maximum sustainable yield]] allows nature to adjust to a new steady state, without compromising future harvests. However, this view is naive, because constancy is not an attribute of marine ecosystems, which dooms this approach. Stock abundance fluctuates naturally, changing the potential yield over short and long-term periods.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n* ''Preserving intergenerational equity'' acknowledges natural fluctuations and regards as unsustainable only practices which damage the [[gene]]tic structure<!--what is \"the genetic structure\"?--> [[habitat loss|destroy habitat]], or deplete [[Fish stock|stock levels]] to the point where rebuilding requires more than a single generation. Providing rebuilding takes only one generation, [[overfishing]] may be economically foolish, but it is not unsustainable. This definition is widely accepted.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n* ''Maintaining a biological, social and economic system'' considers the health of the human ecosystem as well as the marine ecosystem. A fishery which rotates among multiple species can deplete individual stocks and still be sustainable so long as the ecosystem retains its intrinsic integrity.<!-- this term needs definition --> Such a definition might consider as sustainable fishing practices that lead to the reduction and possible extinction of some species.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n\n===Social sustainability===\nFisheries and aquaculture are, directly or indirectly, a source of livelihood for over 500 million people, mostly in developing countries.<ref>[http://www.fao.org/fishery/docs/brochure/climate_change/policy_brief.pdf Fisheries and Aquaculture in our Changing Climate]   Policy brief of the [[FAO]] for the [[UNFCCC]] [[United Nations Climate Change Conference 2009|COP-15]] in [[Copenhagen]], December 2009.</ref>\n\nSocial sustainability can conflict with biodiversity. A fishery is socially sustainable if the fishery ecosystem maintains the ability to deliver products the society can use. Major species shifts within the ecosystem could be acceptable as long as the flow of such products continues.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" /> Humans have been operating such regimes for thousands of years, transforming many ecosystems, depleting or driving to extinction many species.<ref>\nJohannes R (1981) ''Words of the lagoon: Fishing and Marine Lore in the Palau District of Micronesia'', University of California Press. {{ISBN|0-520-03929-7}}</ref>\n\n{{rquote|left|''To a great extent, sustainability is like good art, it is hard to describe but we know it when we see it.''|[[Ray Hilborn]]|<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />}}\n\nAccording to Hilborn, the \"loss of some species, and indeed transformation of the ecosystem is not incompatible with sustainable harvests.\"<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" /> For example, in recent years, [[barndoor skate]]s have been caught as [[bycatch]] in the western Atlantic. Their numbers have severely declined and they will probably go extinct if these catch rates continue.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.281.5377.690 |pmid=9685260 |title=Near Extinction of a Large, Widely Distributed Fish |journal=Science |volume=281 |issue=5377 |pages=690\u2013692 |year=1998 |last1=Casey |first1=J. M. }}</ref> Even if the barndoor skate goes extinct, changing the ecosystem, there could still be sustainable fishing of other commercial species.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Reconciling fisheries with conservation==\n[[File:Grizzly bear with salmon - journal.pbio.1001304.g001.png|thumb|right|Management goals might consider the [[Salmon run#Keystone species|impact of salmon]] on bear and river ecosystems]]\n\nAt the Fourth World Fisheries Congress in 2004, [[Daniel Pauly]] asked, \"How can fisheries science and conservation biology achieve a reconciliation?\", then answered his own question, \"By accepting each other\u2019s \nessentials: that fishing should remain a viable occupation; and that aquatic ecosystems and their biodiversity are allowed to persist.\"<ref>\n[[Daniel Pauly|Pauly, Daniel]] (2004) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/DPkeynote.pdf Reconciling Fisheries with Conservation: the Challenge of Managing Aquatic Ecosystems] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726113148/http://www.seaaroundus.org/DPkeynote.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }} Fourth World Fisheries Congress, Vancouver, 2004.</ref>\n\nA relatively new concept is relationship farming. This is a way of operating farms so they restore the [[food chain]] in their area. Re-establishing a healthy food chain can result in the farm automatically filtering out impurities from feed water and air, feeding its own food chain, and additionally producing high net yields for harvesting. An example is the large cattle ranch [[Veta La Palma]] in southern Spain. Relationship farming was first made popular by [[Joel Salatin]] who created a 220 hectare relationship farm featured prominently in [[Michael Pollan|Michael Pollan's]] book ''[[The Omnivore's Dilemma]]'' (2006) and the documentary films, [[Food, Inc.]] and [[Fresh (2009 film)|Fresh]]. The basic concept of relationship farming is to put effort into building a healthy food chain, and then the food chain does the hard work.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Obstacles==\n[[File:Elevation.jpg|thumb|330px|left|{{legend|#03FCDE|Large areas of the global continental shelf, highlighted in cyan, have had heavy bottom trawls repeatedly dragged over them}}]]\n\n===Overfishing===\n{{main|Overfishing}}\nOverfishing can be sustainable. According to Hilborn, overfishing can be \"a misallocation of societies' resources\", but it does not necessarily threaten conservation or sustainability\".<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n\n[[Overfishing]] is traditionally defined as harvesting so many fish that the yield is less than it would be if fishing were reduced.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" /> For example, [[Pacific salmon]] are usually managed by trying to determine how many spawning salmon, called the \"[[escapement]]\", are needed each generation to produce the maximum harvestable surplus. The optimum escapement is that needed to reach that surplus. If the escapement is half the optimum, then normal fishing looks like overfishing. But this is still sustainable fishing, which could continue indefinitely at its reduced stock numbers and yield. There is a wide range of escapement sizes that present no threat that the stock might collapse or that the stock structure might erode.<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n\nOn the other hand, overfishing can precede severe stock depletion and fishery collapse.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ludwig | first1 = D | last2 = Hilborn | first2 = R | last3 = Walter | first3 = C | year = 1993 | title = Uncertainty, resource exploitation and conservation: Lessons from history | url = http://www.bren.ucsb.edu/academics/courses/595CC/Readings/Ludwig_et_al_1993.pdf | journal = Science | volume = 230 | issue =  5104| pages = 17\u201326 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120502143728/http://www.bren.ucsb.edu/academics/courses/595CC/Readings/Ludwig_et_al_1993.pdf | archive-date = 2012-05-02 | df =  | doi = 10.1126/science.260.5104.17 | pmid = 17793516 }}</ref> Hilborn points out that continuing to exert fishing pressure while production decreases, stock collapses and the fishery fails, is largely \"the product of institutional failure.\"<ref name=\"Hilborn2005\" />\n\nToday over 70% of fish species are either fully exploited, overexploited, depleted, or recovering from depletion. If overfishing does not decrease, it is predicted that stocks of all species currently commercially fished for will collapse by 2048.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/blue_planet/problems/problems_fishing/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110417143412/http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/blue_planet/problems/problems_fishing/ |archive-date=2011-04-17 |df= }}</ref>\u201d\n\nA Hubbert linearization ([[Hubbert curve]]) has been applied to the [[whaling]] industry, as well as charting the price of [[caviar]], which depends on [[sturgeon]] stocks.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.aspoitalia.net/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=34&Itemid=39 |title=ASPO Italia |access-date=2013-11-03 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929002232/http://www.aspoitalia.net/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=34&Itemid=39 |archive-date=2007-09-29 |df= }}</ref> Another example is [[North Sea]] [[cod]]. Comparing fisheries and mineral extraction tells us that human pressure on the environment is causing a wide range of resources to go through a Hubbert depletion cycle.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.hubbertpeak.com/laherrere/multihub.htm |title=Laherrere: Multi-Hubbert Modeling |access-date=2013-11-03 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028052636/http://www.hubbertpeak.com/laherrere/multihub.htm |archive-date=2013-10-28 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s10668-007-9108-1 |title=Silent water: A brief examination of the marine fisheries crisis |journal=Environment, Development and Sustainability |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=255\u2013263 |year=2007 |last1=Jacquet |first1=Jennifer }}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 220\n | header            = \n | header_align      = \n | header_background = \n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = \n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | image2    = Fishing down the food web.jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = Fishing down the [[food web]]\n | image3    = Bangladesh Fishing 2006.jpg\n | alt3      = \n | caption3  = Coastal fishing communities in Bangladesh are vulnerable to flooding from sea-level rises.<ref>\nSarwar G.M. (2005) \"[http://www.lumes.lu.se/database/alumni/04.05/theses/golam_sarwar.pdf Impacts of Sea Level Rise on the Coastal Zone of Bangladesh] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815093552/http://www.lumes.lu.se/database/alumni/04.05/theses/golam_sarwar.pdf |date=2012-08-15 }}\" Masters thesis. [[Lund University]].</ref>\n | image4    = Maldives - Kurumba Island.jpg\n | alt4      = \n | caption4  = Island with [[fringing reef]] in the [[Maldives]]. [[Coral reef]]s are dying around the world.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/interactive/2009/sep/02/coral-world-interactive Coral reefs around the world] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305013004/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/interactive/2009/sep/02/coral-world-interactive |date=2017-03-05 }} ''[[Guardian.co.uk]]'', 2 September 2009.</ref>\n | image5    = Aralsee.gif\n | alt5      = \n | caption5  = Shrinking of the Aral Sea\n}}\n\n===Habitat modification===\n{{see also|Environmental effects of fishing|Destructive fishing practices}}\n\nNearly all the world's [[continental shelf|continental shelves]], and large areas of [[continental slope]]s, underwater ridges, and [[seamount]]s, have had heavy [[Bottom trawling|bottom trawls]] and [[Fishing dredge|dredges]] repeatedly dragged over their surfaces. For fifty years, governments and organizations, such as the [[Asian Development Bank]], have encouraged the fishing industry to develop trawler fleets. Repeated [[bottom trawling]] and dredging literally flattens diversity in the [[benthic]] habitat, radically changing the associated communities.<!-- trawling and dredging is unsustainable now and forever?--><ref name=\"Watling2005\">\nWatling, Les (2005) [http://www.mcbi.org/what/what_pdfs/Watling_2005.pdf \"The global destruction of bottom habitats by mobile fishing gear\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013124302/http://www.mcbi.org/what/what_pdfs/Watling_2005.pdf |date=2008-10-13 }} Chapter 12, pp. 198\u2013210, in Norse and Crowder (2005).</ref>\n\n===Changing the ecosystem balance===\n{{main|Fishing down the food web}}\n\nSince 1950, 90 percent of 25 species of big predator fish have gone.\n* How we are emptying our seas, ''The Sunday Times'', May 10, 2009.\n* [[Daniel Pauly|Pauly, Daniel]] (2004) [http://fisheries.org/bookstore/all-titles/afs-symposia/54049p Reconciling Fisheries with Conservation: the Challenge of Managing Aquatic Ecosystems] Fourth World Fisheries Congress, Vancouver, 2004.\n\n===Climate change===\n{{main|Fisheries and climate change}}\n\nRising ocean temperatures<ref>\n[http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar4/wg1/ar4-wg1-chapter5.pdf Observations: Oceanic Climate Change and Sea Level] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513164252/http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar4/wg1/ar4-wg1-chapter5.pdf |date=2017-05-13 }} In: ''Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis''. Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. (15MB).</ref> and [[ocean acidification]]<ref>\nDoney, S. C. (2006) \"[http://www.precaution.org/lib/06/ocean_acidification_from_c02_060301.pdf The Dangers of Ocean Acidification] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042304/http://www.precaution.org/lib/06/ocean_acidification_from_c02_060301.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }}\" ''Scientific American'', March 2006.</ref> are radically altering [[aquatic ecosystem]]s. [[Climate change]] is modifying fish distribution<ref>\nCheung, W.W.L., et al. (2009) \"[http://www.seaaroundus.org/ClimateChange/images/Pew%20OSS%20Final%20climate%20change%20and%20fisheries.pdf Redistribution of Fish Catch by Climate Change. A Summary of a New Scientific Analysis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726113553/http://www.seaaroundus.org/ClimateChange/images/Pew%20OSS%20Final%20climate%20change%20and%20fisheries.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }}\" Pew Ocean Science Series. Oct 2009.</ref> and the productivity of marine and freshwater species. This reduces sustainable catch levels across many habitats, puts pressure on resources needed for [[aquaculture]], on the communities that depend on fisheries, and on the oceans' ability to capture and store carbon ([[biological pump]]). [[Sea level rise]] puts coastal [[fishing community|fishing communities]] at risk, while changing rainfall patterns and water use impact on inland (freshwater) fisheries and aquaculture.\n\n===Ocean pollution===\n{{main|Marine pollution}}\n\nA recent survey of global ocean health concluded that all parts of the ocean have been affected by human development and that 41 percent has been fouled with human polluted runoff, [[overfishing]], and other abuses.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1149345 |pmid=18276889 |title=A Global Map of Human Impact on Marine Ecosystems |journal=Science |volume=319 |issue=5865 |pages=948\u2013952 |year=2008 |last1=Halpern |first1=Benjamin S. |last2=Walbridge |first2=Shaun |last3=Selkoe |first3=Kimberly A. |last4=Kappel |first4=Carrie V. |last5=Micheli |first5=Fiorenza |last6=d'Agrosa |first6=Caterina |last7=Bruno |first7=John F. |last8=Casey |first8=Kenneth S. |last9=Ebert |first9=Colin |last10=Fox |first10=Helen E. |last11=Fujita |first11=Rod |last12=Heinemann |first12=Dennis |last13=Lenihan |first13=Hunter S. |last14=Madin |first14=Elizabeth M. P. |last15=Perry |first15=Matthew T. |last16=Selig |first16=Elizabeth R. |last17=Spalding |first17=Mark |last18=Steneck |first18=Robert |last19=Watson |first19=Reg |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9a1d46fa70f2ef9607feffa92eaadc2d4784aa05 }}</ref> [[Pollution]] is not easy to fix, because pollution sources are so dispersed, and are built into the economic systems we depend on.\n\nThe [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP) mapped the impacts of stressors such as climate change, pollution, [[exotic species]], and [[over-exploitation]] of resources on the oceans. The report shows at least 75 percent of the world's key fishing grounds may be affected.<ref>\n[http://www.coml.org/discoveries/index.htm Census of Marine Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202002502/http://www.coml.org/discoveries/index.htm |date=2008-12-02 }} \u2014 the largest oceanographic project in history.</ref><ref>\nNellemann, C., Hain, S., and Alder, J. (Eds). February 2008. In Dead Water: Merging of climate change with pollution, over-harvest, and infestations in the world\u2019s fishing grounds. United Nations Environment Programme, GRID-Arendal, Norway. Available at {{cite web |url=http://www.unep.org/pdf/InDeadWater_LR.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-09-15 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090707235423/http://www.unep.org/pdf/InDeadWater_LR.pdf |archive-date=2009-07-07 |df= }} Off-site Link</ref><ref>\nThe New York Times, 9 March 2008 Available at: {{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/09/opinion/09sun2.html?ref=todayspaper |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-09-15 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510210716/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/09/opinion/09sun2.html?ref=todayspaper |archive-date=2013-05-10 |df= |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2008-03-09 }} Off-site Link</ref>\n\n===Diseases and toxins===\n{{see also|Fish diseases and parasites|Harmful algal blooms|Mercury in fish}}\n\nLarge predator  fish can  contain significant amounts of mercury, a neurotoxin which can affect [[fetal development]], memory, mental focus, and produce tremors.\n\n===Irrigation===\n[[File:Aralship2.jpg|thumb|Abandoned ship near [[Aral, Kazakhstan]].]]\n\nLakes are dependent on the inflow of water from its [[drainage basin]]. In some areas, aggressive irrigation has caused this inflow to decrease significantly, causing water depletion and a shrinking of the lake. The most notable example is the [[Aral Sea]], formerly among the four [[largest lakes]] in the world, now only a tenth of its former surface area.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Remediation==\n\n===Fisheries management===\n{{main|Fisheries management}}\n\n[[Fisheries management]] draws on [[fisheries science]] to enable sustainable exploitation. Modern fisheries management is often defined as mandatory rules based on concrete objectives and a mix of management techniques, enforced by a [[monitoring control and surveillance]] system.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1467-2979.2007.00263_2.x |title=Managing fisheries is managing people: What has been learned? |journal=Fish and Fisheries |volume=8 |issue=4 |pages=285\u2013296 |year=2007 |last1=Hilborn |first1=Ray }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1579/0044-7447(2007)36[290:tsaupd]2.0.co;2 |title=The ''Sea'' Around Us ''Project'': Documenting and Communicating Global Fisheries Impacts on Marine Ecosystems |journal=AMBIO: A Journal of the Human Environment |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=290\u2013295 |year=2007 |last1=Pauly |first1=Daniel }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.fishres.2007.08.017 |title=The world trade organization and global fisheries sustainability |journal=Fisheries Research |volume=88 |issue=1\u20133 |pages=1\u20134 |year=2007 }}</ref>\n\n* Ideas and rules: Economist [[Paul Romer]] believes sustainable growth is possible providing the right ideas (technology) are combined with the right rules, rather than simply hectoring fishers. There has been no lack of innovative ideas about how to harvest fish. He characterizes failures as primarily failures to apply appropriate rules.<ref>\n[http://chartercities.org/blog/34/fish-proverb-v20-bringing-in-rules Fish Proverb v2.0 (Bringing in Rules)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919000650/http://chartercities.org/blog/34/fish-proverb-v20-bringing-in-rules |date=2009-09-19 }} [[Paul Romer]], 29 July 2009.</ref><ref>[http://blog.ted.com/2009/07/paul_romer_at_t.php Running notes from session 7] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110829062445/http://blog.ted.com/2009/07/paul_romer_at_t.php |date=2011-08-29 }} [[Paul Romer]] at [[TEDGlobal]] 2009.</ref>\n\n* [[Fishing subsidies]]: Government subsidies influence many of the world fisheries. Operating cost subsidies allow European and Asian [[fishing fleet]]s to fish in distant waters, such as West Africa. Many experts reject fishing subsidies and advocate restructuring incentives globally to help struggling fisheries recover.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/450945a |pmid=18075556 |title=All fishing nations must unite to cut subsidies |journal=Nature |volume=450 |issue=7172 |pages=945 |year=2007 |last1=Sumaila |first1=U. Rashid |last2=Pauly |first2=Daniel }}</ref><ref>\nClark C, Munro G and [[Ussif Rashid Sumaila|Sumaila UR]] (2004) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/SUBSIDIES.PDF Subsidies, Decommissioning Schemes and Effective Fisheries Management] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726113401/http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/SUBSIDIES.PDF |date=2011-07-26 }} Fourth World Fisheries Congress, Vancouver, 2004.</ref>\n\n* Economics: Another focus of conservationists is on curtailing detrimental human activities by improving fisheries' market structure with techniques such as salable [[IFQ|fishing quotas]], like those set up by the [[Northwest Atlantic Fisheries Organization]], or laws such as those listed below.<ref>\n[[Ussif Rashid Sumaila|Sumaila UR]] (2004) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/VALUATION.PDF Valuation and the reconciliation of fisheries with conservation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726113423/http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/VALUATION.PDF |date=2011-07-26 }} Fourth World Fisheries Congress, Vancouver, 2004.</ref>\n\n* Valorization of by-catch: helping to avoid discards (and their associated adverse ecological impacts) by valorizing by-catch products, as they are good sources for protein hydrolizates, peptones, enzymatic mixtures or fish oil being these products of interest different industrial sectors.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.tifs.2010.07.011 |title=Contributing to fisheries sustainability by making the best possible use of their resources: The BEFAIR initiative |journal=Trends in Food Science & Technology |volume=21 |issue=11 |pages=569\u2013578 |year=2010 |last1=Alonso |first1=Antonio A. |last2=Antelo |first2=Luis T. |last3=Otero-Muras |first3=Irene |last4=P\u00e9rez-G\u00e1lvez |first4=Ra\u00fal |hdl=10261/48145 }}</ref>\n*[[Payment for ecosystem services|Payment for Ecosystem Services]]: Environmental Economist, Essam Y Mohammed, argues that by creating direct economic incentives, whereby people are able to receive payment for the services their property provides, will help to establish sustainable fisheries around the world as well as inspire conservation where it otherwise would not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shapingsustainablemarkets.iied.org/direct-economic-incentives-sustainable-fisheries-management-case-hilsa-conservation-bangladesh|title=Direct economic incentives for sustainable fisheries management: the case of Hilsa conservation in Bangladesh - Shaping Sustainable Markets|author=|date=|website=shapingsustainablemarkets.iied.org|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204060043/http://shapingsustainablemarkets.iied.org/direct-economic-incentives-sustainable-fisheries-management-case-hilsa-conservation-bangladesh|archive-date=4 December 2013|df=}}</ref>\n* Sustainable fisheries certification: A promising direction is the independent certification programs for sustainable fisheries conducted by organizations such as the [[Marine Stewardship Council]] and [[Friend of the Sea]]. These programs work at raising consumer awareness and insight into the nature of their seafood purchases.\n* Ecosystem based fisheries: See next section\n\n===Ecosystem based fisheries===\n{{quotebox|''We propose that rebuilding ecosystems, and not sustainability per se, should be the goal of fishery management. Sustainability is a deceptive goal because human harvesting of fish leads to a progressive simplification of ecosystems in favour of smaller, high turnover, lower trophic level fish species that are adapted to withstand disturbance and habitat degradation.''|[[Tony J. Pitcher|Tony Pitcher]] and [[Daniel Pauly]]|<ref>Pitcher TJ and Pauly D (1998) [http://www.accordsdepeche.com/fichiers/docs/bibli_08/873.pdf \"Rebuilding ecosystems, not sustainability, as the proper goal of fishery management\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513143826/http://www.accordsdepeche.com/fichiers/docs/bibli_08/873.pdf |date=2013-05-13 }} Pages 311-325 in T Pitcher, D Pauly and P Hart, ''Reinventing Fisheries Management'', Chapman & Hall.</ref> |width  = 30% |align  = right}}\n\nAccording to [[Marine ecology|marine ecologist]] Chris Frid, the [[fishing industry]] points to [[marine pollution]] and [[global warming]] as the causes of recent, unprecedented declines in fish populations. Frid counters that [[overfishing]] has also altered the way the [[ecosystem]] works. \"Everybody would like to see the rebuilding of fish stocks and this can only be achieved if we understand all of the influences, human and natural, on fish dynamics.\u201d He adds: \u201cfish communities can be altered in a number of ways, for example they can decrease if particular-sized individuals of a species are targeted, as this affects [[Population dynamics of fisheries#Predator-prey equations|predator and prey dynamics]]. Fishing, however, is not the sole cause of changes to [[marine life]]&mdash;[[Marine pollution|pollution]] is another example....No one factor operates in isolation and components of the ecosystem respond differently to each individual factor.\"<ref>\nUniversity of Liverpool (2006). [https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2006/02/060216233254.htm \"Marine Ecologists To Help Rebuild Decreasing Fish Stocks\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918202628/https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2006/02/060216233254.htm |date=2017-09-18 }} '''ScienceDaily'''.</ref>\n\nThe traditional approach to fisheries science and management has been to focus on a single species. This can be contrasted with the [[Ecosystem Approach|ecosystem-based approach]]. Ecosystem-based fishery concepts have been implemented in some regions.<!--which regions?--><ref>\n[[Villy Christensen|Christensen, Villy]] (2004) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/ECOSYSTEMMODELING.PDF Using ecosystem modeling for fisheries management and marine ecosystem conservation: Where are we?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726113323/http://www.seaaroundus.org/4WFC/ECOSYSTEMMODELING.PDF |date=2011-07-26 }} Fourth World Fisheries Congress, Vancouver, 2004.</ref> In a 2007 effort to \"stimulate much needed discussion\" and \"clarify the essential components\" of ecosystem-based fisheries science, a group of scientists offered the following '''ten commandments for ecosystem-based fisheries scientists'''<ref>\nFrancis RC, Hixon MA, Clarke ME, Murawski SA, and Ralston S (2007) [http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/newsarch/2007/Feb07/commandments.html ''Ten commandments for ecosystem-based fisheries scientists''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115205500/http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/newsarch/2007/Feb07/commandments.html |date=2009-01-15 }} Proceedings of Coastal Zone 07, Portland, Oregon. [http://www.csc.noaa.gov/cz/2007/Coastal_Zone_07_Proceedings/PDFs/Tuesday_Abstracts/0000.Hixon.pdf Download] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217092611/http://www.csc.noaa.gov/cz/2007/Coastal_Zone_07_Proceedings/PDFs/Tuesday_Abstracts/0000.Hixon.pdf |date=2008-12-17 }}</ref>\n{{quote|\n* Keep a perspective that is holistic, risk-adverse and adaptive.\n* Maintain an \u201cold growth\u201d structure in fish populations, since big, old and fat female fish have been shown to be the best spawners, but are also susceptible to overfishing.\n* Characterize and maintain the natural spatial structure of fish stocks, so that management boundaries match natural boundaries in the sea.\n* Monitor and maintain seafloor habitats to make sure fish have food and shelter.\n* Maintain resilient ecosystems that are able to withstand occasional shocks.\n* Identify and maintain critical food-web connections, including predators and forage species.\n* Adapt to ecosystem changes through time, both short-term and on longer cycles of decades or centuries, including global climate change.\n* Account for evolutionary changes caused by fishing, which tends to remove large, older fish.\n* Include the actions of humans and their social and economic systems in all ecological equations.\n||}}\n\n===Marine protected areas===\n{{main|Marine protected areas}}\nStrategies and techniques for marine conservation tend to combine theoretical disciplines, such as population biology, with practical conservation strategies, such as setting up protected areas, as with [[Marine protected area|Marine Protected Area]]s (MPAs) or [[Voluntary Marine Conservation Area]]s. Each nation defines MPAs independently, but they commonly involve increased protection for the area from fishing and other threats.<ref>\nWood, L. J. (2007).  [http://www.mpaglobal.org MPA Global: A database of the world's marine protected areas.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814080930/http://www.mpaglobal.org/ |date=2009-08-14 }} [[Sea Around Us Project]], UNEP-WCMC & [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]. Available at www.mpaglobal.org. Off-site Link MPA News, March 2008</ref>\n\nMarine life is not evenly distributed in the oceans. Most of the really valuable ecosystems are in relatively shallow coastal waters, above or near the [[continental shelf]], where the sunlit waters are often nutrient rich from [[land runoff]] or [[upwelling]]s at the continental edge, allowing photosynthesis, which energizes the lowest trophic levels. In the 1970s, for reasons more to do with [[oil drilling]] than with fishing, the U.S. extended its jurisdiction, then 12 miles from the coast, to 200 miles. This made huge shelf areas part of its territory. Other nations followed, extending national control to what became known as the [[exclusive economic zone]] (EEZ). This move has had many implications for fisheries conservation, since it means that most of the most productive maritime ecosystems are now under national jurisdictions, opening possibilities for protecting these ecosystems by passing appropriate laws.\n\n[[Daniel Pauly]] characterises marine protected areas as \"a conservation tool of revolutionary importance that is being incorporated into the fisheries mainstream.\"<ref name=\"Preikshot&Pauly2005\" /> [[The Pew Charitable Trusts]] have funded various initiatives aimed at encouraging the development of MPAs and other ocean conservation measures.<ref>\n[http://www.fishingnj.org/netusa17.htm Pew, SeaWeb shrug off oil to target fishing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713131144/http://www.fishingnj.org/netusa17.htm |date=2010-07-13 }}. Retrieved 11 October 2009.</ref><ref>\n[[Callum Roberts|Roberts, Callum]] (2007) [http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/ ''The Unnatural History of the Sea: The Past and Future of Humanity and Fishing''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090906131727/http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/ |date=2009-09-06 }} Island Press.  {{ISBN|978-1-85675-294-7}}</ref><ref>\n[http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/sealife/index.htm Protecting Sea Life: Marine Reserves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017063119/http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/sealife/index.htm |date=2009-10-17 }} [[Callum Roberts]]. Retrieved 20 September 2009.</ref><ref>\n[http://www.wildlifetrusts.org/?section=marinebill:seasofplenty Seas of Plenty] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901164526/http://www.wildlifetrusts.org/?section=marinebill:seasofplenty |date=2009-09-01 }} ''[[The Wildlife Trusts]]''.</ref>\n\n===Fish farming===\n{{see also|Salmon farming issues}}\n\nThere exists concerns that [[Fish farm|farmed fish]] cannot produce necessary yields efficiently. For example, farmed salmon eat three pounds of wild fish to produce one pound of salmon.<ref>\n[http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=4286 Fish Info Network from Globefish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109223151/http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=4286 |date=2007-11-09 }} Globefish is the unit in the Fisheries Department of the [[FAO]] responsible for information on international fish trade.</ref><ref>\nMann, C. C. (2004). The Bluewater Revolution. Wired Magazine, 12:05, www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.05/fish.html Off-site Link</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Naylor | first1 = R. L. | last2 = Goldburg | first2 = R. J. | last3 = Primavera | first3 = J. | last4 = Kautsky | first4 = N. | last5 = Beveridge | first5 = M. C. M. | last6 = Clay | first6 = J. | last7 = Folke | first7 = C. | last8 = Lubchenco | first8 = J. | last9 = Mooney | first9 = H. | last10 = Troel | first10 = M. | year = 2001 | title = Effects of Aquaculture on World Fish Supplies. | url = http://www.esa.org/science_resources/issues/FileEnglish/issue8.pdf | journal = Issues in Ecology | volume = 8 | issue =  | pages = 1\u201314 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120511152412/http://esa.org/science_resources/issues/FileEnglish/issue8.pdf | archive-date = 2012-05-11 | df =  | access-date = 2017-04-21 }}</ref><ref>\n[http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0704/feature1/gallery22.html The Greening of the Blue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122134023/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0704/feature1/gallery22.html |date=2009-01-22 }} ''National Geographic Magazine'', April 2007.</ref><ref>\nPauly, D. [http://www.tnr.com/article/environment-energy/aquacalypse-now?page=0,2 \"Aquacalypse Now\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004154819/http://www.tnr.com/article/environment-energy/aquacalypse-now?page=0,2 |date=2009-10-04 }} ''The New Republic'', September 28, 2009.</ref><ref>\n[http://www.sustainablefish.org/ Sustainable Fisheries Partnership] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329093549/http://www.sustainablefish.org/ |date=2009-03-29 }} Home page.</ref><ref>\nSustainable Fisheries Partnership: [http://media.sustainablefish.org/SAF_briefing_Sep_28_09.pdf SFP Briefing: Sustainable Aquaculture Feeds and Wild Fisheries] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728073200/http://media.sustainablefish.org/SAF_briefing_Sep_28_09.pdf |date=2011-07-28 }} , 2009.</ref><ref>\nSustainable Fisheries Partnership: [http://media.sustainablefish.org/SAF_PR_Sep_28_09.pdf Press Release: Growing issue of sustainable aquaculture feeds present threats and opportunities \u2013 seafood retailers risk charge of \u2018blue-washing\u2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728073712/http://media.sustainablefish.org/SAF_PR_Sep_28_09.pdf |date=2011-07-28 }} September 28, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Laws and treaties===\nInternational laws and treaties related to [[marine conservation]] include the 1966 [[Convention on Fishing and Conservation of Living Resources of the High Seas]]. [[United States]] laws related to marine conservation include the 1972 [[Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972|Marine Mammal Protection Act]], as well as the 1972 [[Ocean Dumping Act|Marine Protection, Research and Sanctuaries Act]] which established the [[U.S. National Marine Sanctuary|National Marine Sanctuaries]] program. [[Magnuson-Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act]].\n\n===Awareness campaigns===\n{{see also|Sustainable seafood advisory lists and certification}}\n[[File:Kalateadlased uurimist\u00f6\u00f6 tulemusi tutvustamas.jpg|thumb|Introducing the results of long term monitoring to a local fishermen in [[Kihnu]], [[Estonia]].]]\nVarious organizations promote sustainable fishing strategies, educate the public and stakeholders, and lobby for conservation law and policy. The list includes the Marine Conservation Biology Institute and [[Blue Frontier Campaign]] in the U.S., The U.K.'s [[Frontier (the Society for Environmental Exploration)]] and [[Marine Conservation Society]], [[Australian Marine Conservation Society]], [[International Council for the Exploration of the Sea]] (ICES), [[Langkawi Declaration]], [[Oceana (non-profit group)|Oceana]], [[PROFISH]], and the [[Sea Around Us Project]], [[International Collective in Support of Fishworkers]], [[World Forum of Fish Harvesters and Fish Workers]], Frozen at Sea Fillets Association and [[CEDO]].\n\nThe United Nations [[Millennium Development Goals]] include, as goal #7: target 2, the intention to \"reduce [[biodiversity loss]], achieving, by 2010, a significant reduction in the rate of loss\", including improving fisheries management to reduce depletion of fish stocks.<ref>\nMillennium Development Report 2008: [https://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/environ.shtml Goal 7: Ensure environmental sustainability] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423031621/http://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/environ.shtml |date=2015-04-23 }}  United Nations.</ref><ref>\n[http://mdgs.un.org/unsd/mdg/Resources/Static/Products/Progress2008/MDG_Report_2008_En.pdf#page=41 Millennium Development Report 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827045721/http://mdgs.un.org/unsd/mdg/Resources/Static/Products/Progress2008/MDG_Report_2008_En.pdf |date=2010-08-27 }} United Nations.</ref>\n\nSome organizations certify fishing industry players for sustainable or good practices, such as the   [[Marine Stewardship Council]] and [[Friend of the Sea]].\n\nOther organizations offer advice to members of the public who eat with an eye to sustainability. According to the marine conservation biologist [[Callum Roberts]], four criteria apply when choosing seafood:<ref>\n[http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/seafood/index.htm Advice for Seafood Lovers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609050530/http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/seafood/index.htm |date=2008-06-09 }} [[Callum Roberts]]. Retrieved 20 September 2009.</ref>\n<blockquote>\n* Is the species in trouble in the wild where the animals were caught?\n* Does fishing for the species damage ocean habitats?\n* Is there a large amount of [[bycatch]] taken with the target species?\n* Does the fishery have a problem with discards&mdash;generally, undersized animals caught and thrown away because their market value is low?\n</blockquote>\n\nThe following organizations have download links for wallet-sized cards, listing good and bad choices:<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pauly | first1 = D. | year = 2007 | title = The rise of consumer awareness campaigns in an era of collapsing fisheries | url = http://www.fisheries.ubc.ca/archive/students/jjacquet/MP31.pdf | journal = Marine Policy | volume = 31 | issue = 3| pages = 308\u2013313 | doi = 10.1016/j.marpol.2006.09.003 }}</ref>\n<blockquote>\n* [[Monterey Bay Aquarium]] [[Seafood Watch]], USA<ref>[http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/seafoodwatch.asp link] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051107094006/http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/seafoodwatch.asp |date=2005-11-07 }}</ref>\n* [[Blue Ocean Institute]], USA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blueocean.org/seafood/|title=Seafoods Archive - The Safina Center|author=|date=|website=The Safina Center|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917192722/http://www.blueocean.org/seafood|archive-date=17 September 2009|df=}}</ref>\n* [[Marine Conservation Society]], UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fishonline.org/|title=Good Fish Guide - Marine Conservation Society|author=|date=|website=www.fishonline.org|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210010636/http://www.fishonline.org/|archive-date=10 December 2015|df=}}</ref>\n* [[Australian Marine Conservation Society]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcs.org.au/default2.asp?active_page_id=137|title=link|author=|date=|website=amcs.org.au|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220064617/http://www.amcs.org.au/default2.asp?active_page_id=137|archive-date=20 December 2008|df=}}</ref>\n* The Southern African Sustainable Seafood Initiative<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org.za/sassi|title=link|author=|date=|website=panda.org.za|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426050845/http://www.panda.org.za/sassi/|archive-date=26 April 2010|df=}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Data issues==\n\n===Data quality===\nOne of the major impediments to the rational control of marine resources is inadequate data. According to fisheries scientist Milo Adkison (2007), the primary limitation in fisheries management decisions is poor data. Fisheries management decisions are often based on population models, but the models need quality data to be accurate. Scientists and fishery managers would be better served with simpler models and improved data.<ref>\n[[University of Alaska Fairbanks]] (2007) [http://www.sfos.uaf.edu/news/story/?ni=184 ''Adkison advocates increased fisheries data gathering''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711045411/http://www.sfos.uaf.edu/news/story/?ni=184 |date=2007-07-11 }}</ref>\n\n===Unreported fishing===\nEstimates of illegal catch losses range between $10 billion and $23 billion annually, representing between 11 and 26 million [[tonne]]s.<ref>[[UBC Fisheries Centre]] (2008) [http://www.mrag.co.uk/Documents/ExtentGlobalIllegalFishing.pdf The Global Extent of Illegal Fishing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520161657/http://www.mrag.co.uk/Documents/ExtentGlobalIllegalFishing.pdf |date=2010-05-20 }} University of British Columbia.</ref>\n\n* [[Incidental catch]]<ref name=\"Preikshot&Pauly2005\" />\n\n===Shifting baselines===\n[[Shifting baseline]]s is the way significant changes to a system are measured against previous baselines, which themselves may represent significant changes from the original state of the system. The term was first used by the [[Fisheries science|fisheries scientist]] [[Daniel Pauly]] in his paper \"Anecdotes and the shifting baseline syndrome of fisheries\".<ref>Pauly (1995)</ref> Pauly developed the term in reference to [[fisheries management]] where fisheries scientists sometimes fail to identify the correct \"[[wiktionary:baseline|baseline]]\" population size (e.g. how abundant a fish species population was ''before'' human exploitation) and thus work with a '''shifted baseline'''. He describes the way that radically depleted fisheries were evaluated by experts who used the state of the fishery at the start of their careers as the baseline, rather than the fishery in its untouched state. Areas that swarmed with a particular species hundreds of years ago, may have experienced long-term decline, but it is the level of decades previously that is considered the appropriate reference point for current populations. In this way large declines in ecosystems or species over long periods of time were, and are, masked. There is a loss of [[perception]] of change that occurs when each [[generation]] redefines what is \"natural\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/baselines/index.htm|title=The Unnatural History of the Sea|author=|date=|website=www.york.ac.uk|access-date=30 April 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710001400/http://www.york.ac.uk/res/unnatural-history-of-the-sea/baselines/index.htm|archive-date=10 July 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\n==''Looting the seas''==\n''Looting the seas'' is the name given by the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] to a series of journalistic investigations into areas directly affecting the sustainability of fisheries. So far they have investigated three areas involving fraud, negligence and overfishing:<ref>[http://www.iwatchnews.org/environment/natural-resources/looting-seas Looting the Seas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304215856/http://www.iwatchnews.org/environment/natural-resources/looting-seas |date=2012-03-04 }} ''iWatch News'', 17 March 2012.</ref>\n* The black market in [[Atlantic bluefin tuna|bluefin tuna]]\n* Subsidies propping up the Spanish fishing industry\n* Overfishing of the [[Chilean jack mackerel|southern jack mackerel]]\n\n==Other factors==\nThe focus of sustainable fishing is often on the fish.   Other factors are sometimes  included in the broader question of sustainability.  The use of [[non-renewable resource]]s is not fully sustainable.  This might include [[diesel fuel]] for the fishing ships and boats: there is even a debate about the long term sustainability of [[biofuel]]s.  Modern [[fishing net]]s are usually made of artificial  [[polyamides]] like [[nylon]].  Synthetic braided [[rope]]s are generally made from nylon, polyester, polypropylene or high performance fibers such as ultra high modulus polyethylene ([[Ultra-high-molecular-weight polyethylene|HMPE]]) and [[aramid]].\n\nEnergy and resources are employed in [[fish processing]], [[refrigeration]], [[packaging]], [[logistics]], etc.  The methodologies of [[Life-cycle assessment]] are useful to evaluate the sustainability of components and systems.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11367-006-0275-3 |title=Impact categories for life cycle assessment research of seafood production systems: Review and prospectus |journal=The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment |volume=12 |issue=6 |pages=414\u2013421 |year=2006 |last1=Pelletier |first1=Nathan L. |last2=Ayer |first2=Nathan W. |last3=Tyedmers |first3=Peter H. |last4=Kruse |first4=Sarah A. |last5=Flysjo |first5=Anna |last6=Robillard |first6=Greg |last7=Ziegler |first7=Friederike |last8=Scholz |first8=Astrid J. |last9=Sonesson |first9=Ulf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.resconrec.2005.10.003 |title=Environmental assessment of canned tuna manufacture with a life-cycle perspective |journal=Resources, Conservation and Recycling |volume=47 |pages=56\u201372 |year=2006 |last1=Hospido |first1=A. |last2=Vazquez |first2=M.E. |last3=Cuevas |first3=A. |last4=Feijoo |first4=G. |last5=Moreira |first5=M.T. }}</ref>  These are part of the broad question of sustainability.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Community-supported fishery]]\n* ''[[The End of the Line: How Overfishing Is Changing the World and What We Eat|The End of the Line]]''\n* [[Ocean Conservancy]]\n* [[International Seafood Sustainability Foundation]]\n* [[Worldwatch Institute]]\n* [[Marine Life Protection Act]]\n* [[Ocean Outcomes]]\n